# PSSMS Architecture Rules

## Stack

- Core backend: NestJS + Fastify + TypeScript (modular monolith)
- AI/vision only: Python FastAPI (`vision-ai-service`, `analytics-ai-service`)
- Frontend: Next.js monorepo — portals are UIs, not microservices
- Data: PostgreSQL (schema-per-domain + RLS), Redis, RabbitMQ, MQTT, MinIO, Keycloak

## Non-negotiables

- **Portal ≠ service** — do not create one backend per portal; build domain libs
- **Module isolation** — no direct cross-module repository access; use ports or events
- **Creator ≠ approver** — use shared `libs/approvals` engine
- **Data separation** — guard attendance ≠ customer employee attendance; enforce `organization_id` / `customer_id` + RLS
- **Payroll** — immutable snapshots; never recompute live from attendance on every page load
- **CCTV** — video stays on NVR/MinIO; Nest receives events/metadata only
- **Start small** — Phase 1 foundation (IAM → enterprise → audit → approvals → customers/contracts) before ops/payroll/AI

## Build order preference

```text
backend foundation first → admin-web for E2E → ops/attendance → access/visitors/parking
→ HR/payroll → finance/procurement → device/AI integrations → executive analytics
```

## Folder ownership

- Business logic: `backend/libs/<domain>/{domain,application,infrastructure,presentation}`
- Deployables: `backend/apps/*` (gateway, core-api, workers, gateways, AI)
- Internal portals: routes inside `frontend/apps/admin-web` where possible
- External portals: separate apps (`customer-web`, `supplier-web`, `visitor-web`, …)

See `docs/architecture/system-architecture.md` and `docs/architecture/ports-allocation.md`.
